{"id":"project-LICHEN-iik3","title":"oscore_option_build allows piv_len in flags nibble without validation","description":"File: lichen/subsys/lichen/oscore/oscore.c
Lines: 1086-1107

The oscore_option_build function validates field lengths but then uses piv_len directly in the flags nibble:

```c
/* Validate field lengths against protocol limits */
if (option->piv_len > OSCORE_PIV_MAX_LEN ||
    option->kid_len > OSCORE_ID_MAX_LEN ||
    option->kid_context_len > OSCORE_ID_CONTEXT_MAX_LEN) {
    return OSCORE_ERR_INVALID_PARAM;
}

/* Flags byte */
uint8_t flags = 0;
if (option->has_kid_context) {
    flags |= 0x10;
}
if (option->has_kid) {
    flags |= 0x08;
}
if (option->has_piv) {
    flags |= option->piv_len;  // piv_len is ORed into lower 3 bits
}
```

The flags byte format per RFC 8613 Section 6.1 uses the lower 3 bits for n (PIV length). Valid range is 0-5 since OSCORE_PIV_MAX_LEN is 5. The validation passes piv_len <= 5, so the 3-bit field can hold values 0-7.

However, if piv_len is exactly 5 (binary 101), only 3 bits are used in flags. This is correct. But the code should explicitly mask to 3 bits for defensive coding:
```c
flags |= (option->piv_len & 0x07);
```

Current code is correct because OSCORE_PIV_MAX_LEN=5 < 8, but adding the mask makes the 3-bit constraint explicit.

